BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (08): SPAIN (ANDALUSIA) OVINE, BTV-4
********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 25 Oct 2013
Source: Europa Sur [in Spanish, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://www.europasur.es/article/comarca/1631263/la/junta/detecta/cuatro/focos/lengua/azul/tarifa/y/castellar.html


The Junta [Board] of Andalusia has detected 4 outbreaks of bluetongue disease, in 4 farms in the Campo de Gibraltar county. The affected holdings are located in the Tarifa (3) and Castellar (1) municipalities. All cases were caused by bluetongue virus (BTV) serotype 4. The Ministry of Agriculture took samples after observing symptoms compatible with this disease in a sheep farm located in Castellar de la Frontera. The confirmed outbreak was published in the Veterinary Health Alert Network (RASVE) of the Ministry of Agriculture on 15 Oct 2013. On 18 Oct 2013, the 3 outbreaks from Tarifa were similarly published.

It had been 6 months since this animal disease, not communicable to humans, had been detected previously, namely in March 2013 in the Campo de Gibraltar. Given the finding of virus circulation, veterinary authorities have reinforced existing prevention measures, monitoring and control in the area, in order to obtain more information on the epidemiological situation of the disease and control the possible spread of the virus, according to the Ministry of Environment. Whereas at present vaccination against bluetongue is voluntary, in order to prevent the spread of the virus and the consequent economic losses from the clinical involvement of animals and trade restrictions, the Ministry recommended vaccination of susceptible animals in the affected areas and neighboring areas. At the same time, an official notification of new outbreaks has been made to the European Commission, other regions and sectors. Anyway, the Ministry of Agriculture of the Board noted that there are not, for the moment, restrictions on the movement of livestock except from the 4 farms concerned in order to avoid transmission of the disease which, they insisted, had no effect on human health and is spread through mosquitoes to the flocks of sheep.

--
communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview Pedigree English Longhorns
