[According to Morocco's reports to the OIE, BTV serotypes 1 and 4 have been circulating there for several years, including the 1st half of 2013. It should thus not surprise that the adjacent Spanish territory, Campo de Gibraltar, is similarly affected by the same serotype(s) of this Culicoides-borne orbivirus. In the EU map of bluetongue "restricted zones", last updated 4 Oct 2013, Spain's southernmost part in Andalusia is colored dark blue (zone I; serotypes 1, 4); see map at http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/bt_restrictedzones-map_2012.jpg. The map conveniently shows the current restriction zones in other European countries, namely Italy (particularly Sardinia, Sicily and Tuscany), Corsica (France), Cyprus and some Greek islands adjacent to Turkey's coast.

Between 2008 and 2010, BTV-8 was also reported in Campo de Gibraltar. Spain reported the absence of this serotype since September 2010 in the presentation to EU's SCFCAH dated 15 Jan 2013. The document is available at http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/presentations/15012013_bluetongue_spain.pdf.

Traditionally, bluetongue is a serious clinical disease in sheep, particularly European breeds. The phenomenon observed during recent years, in Europe, of clinical disease in cattle is rather unusual; cattle (and goats) have been known to be subclinical sentinels for the virus. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/8WIk.]
